Look, let's get Satnam 
on the communications link.

246
00:21:18,276 --> 00:21:20,237
We'll try and cross-reference 
the data.

247
00:21:20,404 --> 00:21:23,490
It's a national park. There's not 
supposed to be posted fences.

248
00:21:23,657 --> 00:21:25,534
I mean, what's going on here?

249
00:21:25,701 --> 00:21:27,452
We're geologists.

250
00:21:28,161 --> 00:21:30,205
Do you usually go digging 
with machine guns?

251
00:21:32,040 --> 00:21:34,042
Major, I'll take care of this. 
Thank you.

252
00:21:34,209 --> 00:21:37,379
- What happened to the lake? 
- That's what we're trying to find out.

253
00:21:37,546 --> 00:21:39,631
We think the entire area 
has become unstable.

254
00:21:39,840 --> 00:21:42,884
I think you should take your kids 
and leave, Mr. Curtis.

255
00:21:44,177 --> 00:21:46,555
You're not by any chance 
the Jackson Curtis...

256
00:21:46,722 --> 00:21:49,099
...who wrote Farewell Atlantis, 
are you?

257
00:21:51,643 --> 00:21:53,103
The very same.

258
00:21:54,229 --> 00:21:56,356
It's actually dedicated to my mom.

259
00:21:57,024 --> 00:21:58,525
That's great.

260
00:21:58,817 --> 00:22:02,612
I read a couple of your short stories 
when I was in college. Yeah.

261
00:22:02,779 --> 00:22:05,449
You know, 
your father is a very talented man.

262
00:22:05,615 --> 00:22:07,951
- Listen up. 
- It's amazing. I'm reading your book.

263
00:22:08,118 --> 00:22:11,455
I'm around day 300, the shuttle has 
just lost communication with Earth.

264
00:22:11,621 --> 00:22:13,540
You're one of the lucky few 
who bought it.

265
00:22:13,707 --> 00:22:15,375
- I didn't buy it. 
- No?

266
00:22:15,584 --> 00:22:17,210
My dad gave it to me.

267
00:22:18,920 --> 00:22:20,088
Let me ask you something.

268
00:22:21,173 --> 00:22:23,800
You believe those people 
would behave so selflessly...

269
00:22:23,967 --> 00:22:26,094
...knowing that their own lives 
were at stake?

270
00:22:26,261 --> 00:22:27,679
I hope so.

271
00:22:27,846 --> 00:22:31,141
The critics said I was naive, 
an unabashed optimist...

272
00:22:31,308 --> 00:22:32,976
...but what do they know, right?

273
00:22:33,143 --> 00:22:34,311
Well...

274
00:22:34,728 --> 00:22:36,980
- Pleasure. 
- It was a great pleasure meeting you.

275
00:22:37,564 --> 00:22:40,400
Major, could you escort these 
good people to the campgrounds?

276
00:22:40,567 --> 00:22:41,735
This is yours.

277
00:22:41,902 --> 00:22:43,236
- Thank you. 
- Yes, sir.

278
00:22:43,403 --> 00:22:44,404
- Take care. 
- Okay.

279
00:22:44,654 --> 00:22:45,781
He was very nice.

280
00:22:45,947 --> 00:22:48,450
You're just saying that 
because he liked my book.

281
00:22:53,705 --> 00:22:57,417
Looks like that boy of yours 
is gonna be smarter than any of us.

282
00:23:02,047 --> 00:23:03,090
What's wrong?

283
00:23:03,256 --> 00:23:05,967
I sent Satnam 
the temperature reading.

284
00:23:06,134 --> 00:23:10,013
My colleagues in Argentina and 
Ontario have almost identical data.

285
00:23:10,180 --> 00:23:12,599
It's so hot here, 
we've had to seal off the mine.

286
00:23:12,766 --> 00:23:15,435
- Double-checked the numbers? 
- Triple-checked, my friend.

287
00:23:15,602 --> 00:23:17,938
I wish we were wrong...

288
00:23:18,271 --> 00:23:19,689
...but we're not.

289
00:23:20,440 --> 00:23:22,776
The Earth's crust is destabilizing.

290
00:23:27,948 --> 00:23:29,241
It's too early.

291
00:23:29,408 --> 00:23:32,911
Adrian, 
you have to begin the evacuation.

292
00:23:34,704 --> 00:23:36,289
My God.

293
00:23:36,623 --> 00:23:40,252
All our scientific advances, 
our fancy machines...

294
00:23:40,418 --> 00:23:43,296
The Mayans saw this coming 
thousands of years ago.

295
00:23:52,389 --> 00:23:54,683
I thought we'd have more time.

296
00:24:02,774 --> 00:24:04,234
Okay.

297
00:24:04,693 --> 00:24:06,319
I want you to pack up your family.

298
00:24:06,486 --> 00:24:09,114
I'm gonna arrange an airlift for you 
from Delhi.

299
00:24:09,281 --> 00:24:10,949
Thank you, my friend.

300
00:24:11,408 --> 00:24:12,742
And good luck.

301
00:24:20,917 --> 00:24:23,170
Ajit.

302
00:24:24,504 --> 00:24:26,339
We are going on a big ship.

303
00:24:30,010 --> 00:24:32,179
- That was so cool. 
- Yeah, that was intense.

304
00:24:32,345 --> 00:24:34,514
- The helicopters. 
- Craziest place I've seen.

305
00:24:34,681 --> 00:24:38,351
- Those helicopters were so cool. 
- Wait. Wait. Wait.

306
00:24:38,518 --> 00:24:40,520
Wait. Sorry. One question:

307
00:24:41,313 --> 00:24:45,942
What did the government guys 
say to you?

308
00:24:48,653 --> 00:24:51,698
Well, they don't like us 
going over their fences...

309
00:24:52,324 --> 00:24:55,869
...and that the whole area 
back there is unstable.

310
00:24:56,036 --> 00:24:58,705
Unstable. They said "unstable"?

311
00:24:58,872 --> 00:24:59,956
Yeah, unstable.

312
00:25:02,292 --> 00:25:03,877
That's funny.

313
00:25:04,044 --> 00:25:06,296
Let's go. Have a good one.

314
00:25:08,798 --> 00:25:11,134
Unstable.

315
00:25:16,056 --> 00:25:17,933
It's not just Yellowstone, sir.

316
00:25:18,099 --> 00:25:20,727
Temperatures are rising 
with incredible velocity...

317
00:25:20,894 --> 00:25:22,479
...in hot zones across the globe.

318
00:25:22,646 --> 00:25:24,940
Are you absolutely sure 
about this, Adrian?

319
00:25:25,106 --> 00:25:26,775
Because once we give 
these orders...

320
00:25:26,942 --> 00:25:29,110
...there's no going back. 
You understand that?

321
00:25:29,277 --> 00:25:32,197
I'm afraid there's no longer 
any doubt, sir.

322
00:25:32,364 --> 00:25:36,743
We have to save what we can. 
And we have to move now!

323
00:26:06,564 --> 00:26:09,859
There's mosquitoes in here. 
Did anybody spray the tent?

324
00:26:10,777 --> 00:26:12,445
I'm gonna get that spray tomorrow.

325
00:26:12,612 --> 00:26:15,615
They just like you 
because your blood's so sweet.

326
00:26:16,533 --> 00:26:19,202
Dad, you said you wouldn't work 
on your book.

327
00:26:19,369 --> 00:26:22,831
What, Lil'bee? I'm not, I'm not. 
I'm just... I'm doing something else.

328
00:26:23,331 --> 00:26:26,293
Let me get you ready for... 
Ready for bed.

329
00:26:26,459 --> 00:26:28,128
Okay.

330
00:26:30,839 --> 00:26:32,632
Did you really need all these hats?

331
00:26:32,841 --> 00:26:35,552
- Where are your Pull-Ups, sweetie? 
- I have them on.

332
00:26:43,184 --> 00:26:44,686
We have a listener calling in.

333
00:26:44,853 --> 00:26:47,897
Bill from Cooke City, 
you're on the Charlie Frost Show.

334
00:26:48,064 --> 00:26:50,108
Charlie, just wanted to say 
I love your show.

335
00:26:50,275 --> 00:26:51,401
No way.

336
00:26:51,568 --> 00:26:53,194
...not afraid to tell the truth.

337
00:26:53,361 --> 00:26:55,196
Thank you, Bill. 
What is your question?

338
00:26:55,363 --> 00:26:57,574
I wanted to know, 
where is all this gonna start?

339
00:26:57,741 --> 00:27:01,077
Well, something like this could only 
originate in Hollywood, Bill.

340
00:27:01,244 --> 00:27:03,788
They got the Earth 
cracking under their asses already.

341
00:27:03,955 --> 00:27:06,875
Our family believes in the gospel 
of the Lord Jesus.

342
00:27:07,042 --> 00:27:10,629
- We have nothing to fear, Charlie. 
- Good for you, Bill. Thanks for calling.

343
00:27:10,795 --> 00:27:15,592
This is Charlie Frost reporting live 
from Yellowstone National Park...

344
00:27:15,759 --> 00:27:20,847
...soon to become 
the world's largest active volcano.

345
00:27:21,348 --> 00:27:23,266
I'll be right back, folks.

346
00:27:26,436 --> 00:27:29,314
Do you mind if I join you? 
I wanted to ask you something.

347
00:27:29,481 --> 00:27:31,024
I only got a minute.

348
00:27:31,191 --> 00:27:33,026
Hey. Pickle?

349
00:27:33,401 --> 00:27:36,780
No. I was listening to the broadcast 
and I was wondering...

350
00:27:36,946 --> 00:27:40,742
...what exactly is it 
that's gonna start in Hollywood?

351
00:27:40,950 --> 00:27:42,786
It's the apocalypse.

352
00:27:42,952 --> 00:27:44,704
End of days.

353
00:27:44,871 --> 00:27:48,416
The Judgment Day, 
the end of the world, my friend.

354
00:27:48,583 --> 00:27:52,045
Christians called it the rapture, 
but the Mayans knew about it...

355
00:27:52,212 --> 00:27:55,465
...the Hopis, the I Ching...

356
00:27:55,674 --> 00:27:57,300
...the Bible, kind of...

357
00:27:58,468 --> 00:27:59,511
Beer?

358
00:28:00,303 --> 00:28:02,680
- Yeah. 
- So look, I gotta eat.

359
00:28:02,847 --> 00:28:06,685
Why don't you download my blog. 
It's free.

360
00:28:06,851 --> 00:28:10,146
Of course, 
we do appreciate donations.

361
00:28:10,313 --> 00:28:14,484
In ancient times, the Mayan people 
were the first civilization to discover...

362
00:28:14,693 --> 00:28:17,153
...that this planet had 
an expiration date.

363
00:28:17,320 --> 00:28:18,822
According to their calendar...

364
00:28:18,988 --> 00:28:22,492
...in the year 2012, 
a cataclysmic event will unfold...

365
00:28:22,659 --> 00:28:25,537
...caused by an alignment 
of the planets in our solar system...

366
00:28:25,704 --> 00:28:29,833
...that only happens 
every 640,000 years.

367
00:28:29,082 --> 00:28:31,668
Oh, not again.

368
00:28:31,835 --> 00:28:35,588
Pretty neat, huh? 
I did all the animation myself.

369
00:28:36,131 --> 00:28:39,008
Just imagine the Earth 
as an orange.

370
00:28:39,676 --> 00:28:43,888
You lure them in with humor. 
Then you make them think.

371
00:28:44,055 --> 00:28:47,726
Our sun will begin to emit 
such extreme amounts of radiation...

372
00:28:47,892 --> 00:28:50,103
Those little bastards 
are called neutrinos.

373
00:28:50,270 --> 00:28:53,940
...that the core of the Earth will melt. 
That's the inside part of the orange...

374
00:28:54,107 --> 00:28:57,277
...leaving the crust of our planet 
free to shift.

375
00:28:57,444 --> 00:29:02,198
In 1958, Professor Charles Hapgood 
named it Earth Crust Displacement.

376
00:29:02,365 --> 00:29:05,368
Albert Einstein did support it.

377
00:29:05,535 --> 00:29:06,703
People, we'll get it all.

378
00:29:06,870 --> 00:29:09,747
The forces of Mother Nature 
will be so devastating...

379
00:29:09,914 --> 00:29:15,795
...it will bring an end to this world 
on winter solstice, 12-21-12.

380
00:29:15,962 --> 00:29:20,049
Always remember, folks, 
you heard it first from Charlie Frost.

381
00:29:20,800 --> 00:29:23,553
You'd have to keep a thing like this 
under wraps.

382
00:29:23,762 --> 00:29:25,805
I mean, just think about it, okay?

383
00:29:25,972 --> 00:29:28,558
First, the stock market would go.

384
00:29:28,766 --> 00:29:31,019
Then the economy, boom!

385
00:29:31,186 --> 00:29:32,479
The dollar, boom!

386
00:29:32,645 --> 00:29:37,734
And then pandemonium in the streets. 
War, genocide, boom, boom, boom!

387
00:29:38,318 --> 00:29:41,488
Bullshit. Nobody could keep 
that big a secret, Charlie.

388
00:29:41,654 --> 00:29:44,407
- Somebody would blow the whistle. 
- Every once in a while...

389
00:29:44,574 --> 00:29:46,576
...some poor little sucker tries.

390
00:29:46,784 --> 00:29:49,496
Well, like these guys, boom, boom!

391
00:29:49,662 --> 00:29:53,333
Every one of these guys, 
dead, dead, dead.

392
00:29:56,836 --> 00:29:58,338
That's Professor Meyers.

393
00:29:58,505 --> 00:30:01,341
He ran the Atlantis shuttle program. 
Why, did you know him?

394
00:30:01,508 --> 00:30:03,927
Yeah, he helped me 
with research on my book.

395
00:30:04,093 --> 00:30:06,679
Well, that must have been 
before his "accident. "

396
00:30:06,846 --> 00:30:07,972
Meyers is dead?

397
00:30:08,765 --> 00:30:10,892
Oh, yeah, two months ago.

398
00:30:11,059 --> 00:30:13,812
He was one 
of my most avid listeners...

399
00:30:13,978 --> 00:30:15,939
...and he had it all figured out.

400
00:30:16,105 --> 00:30:19,442
Everything the government was doing, 
where and why...

401
00:30:19,609 --> 00:30:21,820
He even sent me a map.

402
00:30:22,695 --> 00:30:25,907
A map for what, Charlie? 
What's the map for?

403
00:30:32,080 --> 00:30:36,626
They're building spaceships, man.

404
00:30:42,549 --> 00:30:44,467
Shit, man, I have to go...

405
00:30:44,634 --> 00:30:47,929
...because I gotta get back to Earth.

406
00:30:48,096 --> 00:30:50,807
- But do you got a traveler for the road? 
- This is my last...

407
00:30:50,974 --> 00:30:54,143
Oh, that'll be all right. But, anyway, 
I really enjoyed most of this.

408
00:30:54,310 --> 00:30:55,478
Thank you so much.

409
00:30:55,645 --> 00:30:57,480
Hey. Hey, guess what.

410
00:30:57,647 --> 00:31:00,358
- They're selling seats. 
- Put me down for three.

411
00:31:00,525 --> 00:31:01,776
No, guys like you and me 
don't have a chance.

412
00:31:02,819 --> 00:31:05,280
You'd have to be Bill Gates 
or Rupert Murdoch...

413
00:31:05,446 --> 00:31:07,448
...or some Russian billionaire 
or something.

414
00:31:07,615 --> 00:31:09,325
Keep it down, my kids are sleeping.

415
00:31:09,492 --> 00:31:12,245
Get them out of Yellowstone.

416
00:31:12,412 --> 00:31:14,581
It's gonna get ugly here.

417
00:31:16,040 --> 00:31:18,126
Do you have anything 
for mosquito bites?

418
00:31:18,293 --> 00:31:20,128
Before or after?

419
00:31:21,713 --> 00:31:23,047
I'd get before and after.

420
00:31:23,214 --> 00:31:25,967
Stop scratching. 
You're gonna get it all infected.

421
00:31:26,134 --> 00:31:28,303
I had to make a stop 
at the grocery store.

422
00:31:28,469 --> 00:31:31,347
It's Mrs. Birnbaum. 
She's my teacher, she's on TV.

423
00:31:32,390 --> 00:31:35,560
Here is Grayson's Market, which 
was open for business at the time...

424
00:31:35,727 --> 00:31:39,147
...but fortunately, there were 
no fatalities or injuries reported.

425
00:31:39,314 --> 00:31:41,482
It really is a miracle 
that no one got hurt.

426
00:31:42,442 --> 00:31:44,027
Hello? Oh, hi, Mom.

427
00:31:45,320 --> 00:31:48,072
Did you see what happened 
to our supermarket?

428
00:31:50,408 --> 00:31:52,493
She wants us to come home.

429
00:31:52,660 --> 00:31:53,828
is this even possible?

430
00:31:53,995 --> 00:31:56,164
We worked every option 
through the night.

431
00:31:56,331 --> 00:32:00,501
The good news, consensus is that four 
of the arks will be operational in time.

432
00:32:00,668 --> 00:32:02,337
Only four? You call that good news?

433
00:32:02,503 --> 00:32:05,006
We can save over 400,000 people.

434
00:32:05,173 --> 00:32:07,258
To me, sir, 
that's nothing short of a miracle.

435
00:32:07,425 --> 00:32:11,179
But we have to initiate 
the boarding process now. Thomas.

436
00:32:11,596 --> 00:32:13,348
We don't have a choice.

437
00:32:13,514 --> 00:32:15,391
You have got to convince them.

438
00:32:18,061 --> 00:32:19,812
Listen, I'll try to keep this brief.

439
00:32:19,979 --> 00:32:23,024
According to the latest information 
from Yellowsto...

440
00:32:23,191 --> 00:32:26,194
- Please continue, Adrian. 
- Thank you, sir.

441
00:32:26,361 --> 00:32:28,738
The temperature 
of the subterranean crust...

442
00:32:28,905 --> 00:32:32,659
...that is, the cement that holds 
our land mass in place...

443
00:32:32,825 --> 00:32:36,120
...is increasing at a rapid rate, 
much faster than anticipated.

444
00:32:36,287 --> 00:32:39,374
As a result, we've observed 
extreme polar instability.

445
00:32:39,540 --> 00:32:42,335
The magnetic fields have decreased 
by more than 80 percent...

446
00:32:42,502 --> 00:32:44,045
...in the last 48 hours.

447
00:32:44,212 --> 00:32:47,382
How much time do we have, 
Dr. Helmsley?

448
00:32:49,509 --> 00:32:51,386
Two, maybe three days, 
if we're lucky.

449
00:32:52,220 --> 00:32:55,890
How can you speak about luck 
in such a situation?

450
00:32:56,057 --> 00:32:58,810
Apologies, Mr. Prime Minister. I...

451
00:32:58,976 --> 00:33:01,938
I meant no disrespect.

452
00:33:02,563 --> 00:33:07,110
I'm afraid the longer we wait, 
the more luck plays its part.

453
00:33:12,907 --> 00:33:14,242
My friends...

454
00:33:15,576 --> 00:33:17,995
...I recommend 
we evacuate immediately.

455
00:33:20,373 --> 00:33:23,292
If any of you have objections...

456
00:33:24,460 --> 00:33:26,004
...please speak now.

457
00:33:27,004 --> 00:33:28,589
In the blue corner...

458
00:33:30,258 --> 00:33:32,218
...38 victories, 34 knockouts...

459
00:33:32,385 --> 00:33:35,263
...the fighting machine 
from the Ukraine...

460
00:33:35,430 --> 00:33:39,809
...the undefeated number-one ranked 
heavyweight challenger:

461
00:33:39,976 --> 00:33:46,649
Mr. Zultan Balashin!

462
00:34:07,628 --> 00:34:10,465
Kill the bastard, Zultan.

463
00:34:10,631 --> 00:34:13,009
Ladies and gentlemen...

464
00:34:13,176 --> 00:34:17,138
...let's get ready to rumble!

465
00:34:20,475 --> 00:34:22,310
Zultan!

466
00:34:59,430 --> 00:35:03,184
One, two, three...

467
00:35:04,227 --> 00:35:07,563
Caltech believes that the half-mile 
fissure running through Westwood...

468
00:35:07,730 --> 00:35:09,816
...has released 
most of the surface tension.

469
00:35:09,982 --> 00:35:12,860
"Life will soon return to normal," 
Mayor Gonzales said...

470
00:35:13,027 --> 00:35:16,364
- ... at an early news conference. 
- Okay, guys. Almost home.

471
00:35:18,449 --> 00:35:19,534
Rise and shine.

472
00:35:30,211 --> 00:35:32,171
All right, you're free.

473
00:35:33,673 --> 00:35:36,384
- Thank God. 
- Mommy.

474
00:35:37,718 --> 00:35:39,554
Hi, sweetheart.

475
00:35:43,516 --> 00:35:44,934
Gordon!

476
00:35:46,144 --> 00:35:48,187
Hey, buddy boy.

477
00:35:49,105 --> 00:35:51,399
Good time? Yeah?

478
00:35:51,566 --> 00:35:53,234
God, I missed you.

479
00:35:53,401 --> 00:35:54,402
Yeah.

480
00:35:54,569 --> 00:35:56,946
- Who wants pancakes? Come on. 
- Me.

481
00:36:01,242 --> 00:36:04,620
- Thanks for bringing them home early. 
- Yeah.

482
00:36:05,580 --> 00:36:07,081
Pancakes?

483
00:36:08,708 --> 00:36:10,251
Late for work.

484
00:36:21,137 --> 00:36:23,848
- Yes, hello? 
- Curtis, where are you?

485
00:36:24,015 --> 00:36:27,602
- Just getting back from vacation, sir. 
- Good. That is good.

486
00:36:27,768 --> 00:36:30,146
I will send the jet 
to pick up Alec and Oleg.

487
00:36:30,313 --> 00:36:33,274
Yuri bear, tell him to bring 
the raincoat for Caesar.

488
00:36:33,441 --> 00:36:35,776
- It's in the Range Rover. 
- Curtis.

489
00:36:35,943 --> 00:36:38,112
- Yeah? 
- Get my boys as fast as you can.

490
00:36:38,279 --> 00:36:40,281
I'm hurtling towards you 
as we speak, sir.

