it appears that all other 
heads of state are en route...

989
01:17:03,410 --> 01:17:06,038
...with the exception 
of the Italian prime minister...

990
01:17:06,455 --> 01:17:11,084
...who has also decided 
to stay behind and trust in prayer.

991
01:18:18,276 --> 01:18:20,612
The Earth's crust has begun to shift, 
Dr. Helmsley.

992
01:18:20,779 --> 01:18:23,990
- By what degree? 
-1.2 degrees, but it's still moving.

993
01:18:24,157 --> 01:18:25,450
So, what happens next?

994
01:18:25,617 --> 01:18:28,120
Once the movement 
of our land masses comes to a halt...

995
01:18:28,286 --> 01:18:30,080
Let's see a simulation, Scotty.

996
01:18:30,247 --> 01:18:32,499
...expect the formation 
of gigantic tsunamis...

997
01:18:32,666 --> 01:18:35,961
...proportional to the magnitude 
of the corresponding quakes.

998
01:18:53,603 --> 01:18:55,147
From what we have just learned...

999
01:18:54,396 --> 01:18:58,358
...Tokyo seems to have taken 
the full force of the earthquake.

1000
01:18:58,525 --> 01:19:00,777
At this point, 
unconfirmed reports indicate...

1001
01:19:00,944 --> 01:19:03,864
...that large areas of land 
are underwater.

1002
01:19:04,030 --> 01:19:06,199
Please stay tuned for further...

1003
01:19:15,917 --> 01:19:17,586
Tony...

1004
01:19:18,128 --> 01:19:19,713
I called.

1005
01:19:23,300 --> 01:19:25,093
I was too late.

1006
01:19:29,514 --> 01:19:32,809
Maybe they got out in time.

1007
01:19:32,976 --> 01:19:34,978
You never know. They...

1008
01:20:03,256 --> 01:20:04,633
Harry!

1009
01:21:02,232 --> 01:21:04,901
I'm coming home, Dorothy.

1010
01:21:31,303 --> 01:21:32,762
Anything?

1011
01:21:34,180 --> 01:21:37,726
Nothing. Just static. 
Not even an emergency signal.

1012
01:21:51,072 --> 01:21:53,158
Can't think about 
what's going on down there.

1013
01:22:00,582 --> 01:22:02,584
Remember that old Beetle 
we used to camp in?

1014
01:22:02,751 --> 01:22:04,628
We could never get the roof up.

1015
01:22:04,794 --> 01:22:06,379
Yeah.

1016
01:22:06,546 --> 01:22:08,465
We definitely traded up.

1017
01:22:11,426 --> 01:22:13,428
Tried to find our old spot 
at Yellowstone...

1018
01:22:13,845 --> 01:22:15,805
...when I went camping 
with the kids...

1019
01:22:17,015 --> 01:22:18,725
...but I couldn't find it.

1020
01:22:31,071 --> 01:22:34,324
All global ground communication 
has ceased, sir.

1021
01:22:37,118 --> 01:22:40,372
The only signals our satellites 
are picking up...

1022
01:22:40,538 --> 01:22:42,916
...are coming from the vessels 
in Cho Ming.

1023
01:22:43,625 --> 01:22:45,669
Well, there's a piece of good news.

1024
01:22:45,835 --> 01:22:47,087
Any updates, doctor?

1025
01:22:47,253 --> 01:22:50,423
We expect the tsunamis 
to reach landfall in every continent.

1026
01:22:50,590 --> 01:22:54,094
The Cho Ming area will be impacted 
in approximately six hours.

1027
01:22:55,845 --> 01:22:58,890
it looks like the crust has shifted 
by almost 23 degrees...

1028
01:22:59,057 --> 01:23:00,850
...to the southwest.

1029
01:23:01,059 --> 01:23:05,939
The data also shows the Earth's poles 
have reversed their magnetic fields.

1030
01:23:06,106 --> 01:23:07,524
These are their new positions.

1031
01:23:08,441 --> 01:23:09,943
So you're...

1032
01:23:10,735 --> 01:23:13,154
You're telling me 
that the North Pole...

1033
01:23:13,697 --> 01:23:15,949
...is now somewhere in Wisconsin?

1034
01:23:16,116 --> 01:23:18,451
Actually, that's the South Pole now.

1035
01:23:27,210 --> 01:23:29,504
Engine failure. 
Two of the six are down.

1036
01:23:29,671 --> 01:23:31,589
We must get ready.

1037
01:23:32,674 --> 01:23:36,553
- How long do we have? 
- Fifteen minutes. Maybe.

1038
01:23:38,054 --> 01:23:41,016
- Better wake up the kids. 
- Yeah.

1039
01:24:11,755 --> 01:24:13,381
is it time?

1040
01:24:16,551 --> 01:24:19,387
- Dad, what's wrong? 
- Well, Sasha said we gotta land...

1041
01:24:19,554 --> 01:24:23,266
...and it's gonna be a little bumpy 
and maybe a little wet.

1042
01:24:23,433 --> 01:24:24,476
Daddy?

1043
01:24:30,857 --> 01:24:32,067
Hold her steady.

1044
01:24:50,168 --> 01:24:52,462
Daddy, 
I'm not a really good swimmer.

1045
01:24:51,711 --> 01:24:56,716
Hey, no, that's all right. 
That's what you got this for. Right?

1046
01:24:56,883 --> 01:24:59,969
it's like being in a swimming pool, 
only it's got more cool stuff.

1047
01:25:00,136 --> 01:25:03,389
Look, it's got a whistle, 
and a light thing. Right?

1048
01:25:03,556 --> 01:25:05,683
I thought we were going to China.

1049
01:25:06,684 --> 01:25:08,770
No, we gotta land here.

1050
01:25:11,773 --> 01:25:14,025
So we're just all gonna 
stay together, right?

1051
01:25:14,192 --> 01:25:17,153
- No, we're not, we're gonna die. 
- No. We're not.

1052
01:25:17,862 --> 01:25:19,322
Promise?

1053
01:25:19,489 --> 01:25:21,574
I promise you 
we're gonna all stay together...

1054
01:25:21,741 --> 01:25:25,370
...no matter what happens, okay?

1055
01:25:38,550 --> 01:25:40,009
Jackson.

1056
01:25:40,552 --> 01:25:41,886
Yuri.

1057
01:25:43,054 --> 01:25:44,848
I think you better come up here.

1058
01:25:45,557 --> 01:25:47,016
I'm gonna go check this out.

1059
01:25:47,183 --> 01:25:49,185
- Dad. Where are you going? 
- I'll be back.

1060
01:25:49,352 --> 01:25:52,272
- You said you'd stay with us. 
- We gotta buckle up. Let's go.

1061
01:25:53,565 --> 01:25:55,775
Okay, don't ask me 
how that happened...

1062
01:25:55,942 --> 01:25:57,402
...but there is no more ocean...

1063
01:25:57,569 --> 01:25:59,612
...and we're close 
to where we wanted to go.

1064
01:25:59,779 --> 01:26:01,990
it's like the world shifted 
by 1000 miles.

1065
01:26:02,156 --> 01:26:04,742
One thousand five hundrwd 
and seventy-eight to be exact.

1066
01:26:04,909 --> 01:26:07,287
it's called 
Earth Crust Displacement Theory.

1067
01:26:07,495 --> 01:26:09,581
Professor Hapgood, 1958.

1068
01:26:10,456 --> 01:26:11,499
Way to go, Charlie.

1069
01:26:15,587 --> 01:26:16,921
What was that?

1070
01:26:17,922 --> 01:26:20,133
We just lost our last two engines.

1071
01:26:38,902 --> 01:26:42,030
I'm gonna shoot for that glacier. 
it's gonna get rocky.

1072
01:26:42,196 --> 01:26:46,451
Listen, this is gonna sound crazy, 
but here's what you have to do.

1073
01:26:50,079 --> 01:26:52,248
Unbuckle. 
Come on, come on, come on.

1074
01:26:53,791 --> 01:26:55,668
Yuri! What are we doing?

1075
01:26:55,835 --> 01:26:58,338
We are taking the Bentley.

1076
01:26:59,923 --> 01:27:02,467
Not yet. Not yet.

1077
01:27:02,634 --> 01:27:04,177
it has to be perfect.

1078
01:27:04,344 --> 01:27:05,929
Almost there.

1079
01:27:06,095 --> 01:27:08,640
- Come on. 
- Get in the car.

1080
01:27:18,650 --> 01:27:21,402
Okay, go. Now. Pull.

1081
01:27:26,324 --> 01:27:28,826
No, no, no!

1082
01:27:31,829 --> 01:27:33,248
Go. Go, Jackson.

1083
01:27:33,414 --> 01:27:35,917
No, we gotta wait 
for Sasha and Gordon.

1084
01:27:36,084 --> 01:27:39,712
Go. Make sure everybody gets out 
of the plane before I touch down.

1085
01:27:39,879 --> 01:27:40,922
What about you?

1086
01:27:41,089 --> 01:27:45,593
I'll be fine. 
I have to touch this baby down.

1087
01:27:45,677 --> 01:27:47,595
Go!

1088
01:28:02,026 --> 01:28:03,403
There he is. I see him.

1089
01:28:02,652 --> 01:28:06,155
- Wherw is Sasha? Wherw is Sasha? 
- Come on. Let's go.

1090
01:28:06,322 --> 01:28:09,450
He said he's fine. We should get 
out of here before he touches down.

1091
01:28:09,617 --> 01:28:11,786
No, no, no. Don't go. 
We have to wait for him.

1092
01:28:12,328 --> 01:28:14,247
Go, Jackson. Go.

1093
01:28:14,414 --> 01:28:18,084
- Don't go! 
- it won't start. it won't start.

1094
01:28:18,251 --> 01:28:21,754
Just shut up, everybody!

1095
01:28:21,838 --> 01:28:22,880
...start.

1096
01:28:26,300 --> 01:28:28,720
Voice control. Sold me on it.

1097
01:30:08,528 --> 01:30:11,197
Hey! Hey!

1098
01:30:32,093 --> 01:30:34,303
Welcome to 
the People's Republic of China.

1099
01:30:34,887 --> 01:30:37,056
Good to be here. Say hi, kids.

1100
01:30:37,223 --> 01:30:38,307
- Hi. 
- Hi.

1101
01:30:38,474 --> 01:30:40,101
What color are your passes?

1102
01:30:41,769 --> 01:30:44,313
What color 
are your boarding passes?

1103
01:30:46,023 --> 01:30:47,191
I have green card.

1104
01:30:48,401 --> 01:30:50,278
For my boys and me.

1105
01:30:50,445 --> 01:30:51,946
What?

1106
01:30:55,366 --> 01:30:57,535
Yuri. Yuri.

1107
01:30:57,702 --> 01:31:01,080
Yuri, it's a mistake. A joke, right?

1108
01:31:01,247 --> 01:31:02,748
What?

1109
01:31:03,082 --> 01:31:06,460
You think I didn't know 
about you and Sasha?

1110
01:31:08,212 --> 01:31:11,257
May God bless 
that poor bastard's soul.

1111
01:31:16,888 --> 01:31:19,724
I'm sorry, guys. Good luck.

1112
01:31:21,142 --> 01:31:22,894
Come on, boys.

1113
01:31:24,520 --> 01:31:26,564
- Does anybody have any money? 
- I do, I do.

1114
01:31:26,731 --> 01:31:28,191
You got a billion euros?

1115
01:31:33,196 --> 01:31:34,238
Dr. Wilson?

1116
01:31:35,156 --> 01:31:37,742
I'm Captain Michaels, 
skipper of the American ship.

1117
01:31:37,909 --> 01:31:40,161
Please accept my condolences 
for your father.

1118
01:31:40,328 --> 01:31:42,079
Thank you, captain.

1119
01:31:43,456 --> 01:31:46,209
Mr. Anheuser, 
your party is the last to arrive.

1120
01:31:50,463 --> 01:31:52,798
There've been reports 
of severe damage, captain.

1121
01:31:52,965 --> 01:31:54,842
What's the status of Ark Number 3?

1122
01:31:55,009 --> 01:31:57,345
We haven't done 
a complete assessment yet...

1123
01:31:57,512 --> 01:31:59,805
...but it looks like we lost it.

1124
01:32:54,026 --> 01:32:55,861
Leave it to the Chinese.

1125
01:32:56,028 --> 01:32:57,863
I didn't think it was possible.

1126
01:32:58,030 --> 01:32:59,699
Not in the time we had.

1127
01:33:00,283 --> 01:33:01,742
That's Ark Number 3, sir.

1128
01:33:02,660 --> 01:33:05,955
The roof collapsed on it 
during the shifting of the Earth's crust.

1129
01:33:06,872 --> 01:33:08,374
Jesus Christ.

1130
01:33:09,584 --> 01:33:13,045
Boarding of Ark Number 3 will be 
delayed due to technical difficulties.

1131
01:33:13,212 --> 01:33:14,714
- Excuse me. 
- We paid a fortune!

1132
01:33:14,880 --> 01:33:17,883
Please be patient 
as we keep you updated.

1133
01:33:19,093 --> 01:33:21,262
What he said about you and Sasha, 
is it true?

1134
01:33:21,429 --> 01:33:25,182
Sasha was worth 
100 times a man like Yuri.

1135
01:33:25,182 --> 01:33:27,768
I should have listened to you, 
Dr. Silberman.

1136
01:33:27,935 --> 01:33:32,898
I actually liked the way I looked 
before that monster talked me into it.

1137
01:33:33,566 --> 01:33:35,151
You hear that?

1138
01:33:37,903 --> 01:33:39,780
Over there !

1139
01:33:41,324 --> 01:33:42,867
- Hey! 
- Hey!

1140
01:33:43,034 --> 01:33:45,244
- Stop! Stop! Please! 
- Hey! Hold it!

1141
01:33:49,248 --> 01:33:51,000
Hey! Hey!

1142
01:33:51,500 --> 01:33:54,253
Stop! Stop! Stop!

1143
01:33:55,546 --> 01:33:57,173
Help!

1144
01:34:06,515 --> 01:34:07,642
Hey!

1145
01:35:00,152 --> 01:35:01,487
Satnam, where are you?

1146
01:35:01,654 --> 01:35:04,448
- On the Nampan Plateau. 
- What?

1147
01:35:05,658 --> 01:35:07,118
There's a tidal wave 
coming from the east.

1148
01:35:07,284 --> 01:35:11,330
- it's gigantic. 
- Satnam, what happened?

1149
01:35:11,497 --> 01:35:13,624
We never got picked up, Adrian.

1150
01:35:13,791 --> 01:35:16,001
The airlift never came.

1151
01:35:17,503 --> 01:35:19,255
Goodbye, my friend.

1152
01:35:19,880 --> 01:35:25,803
Satnam.

1153
01:35:45,740 --> 01:35:48,659
- The flooding is coming this way? 
- Mary. Where are we set up?

1154
01:35:48,826 --> 01:35:50,286
Over therw.

1155
01:35:53,914 --> 01:35:56,041
Get me the satellite images 
from Nampan, India.

1156
01:35:55,291 --> 01:35:57,918
- Okay, right away. 
- What's happening?

1157
01:35:59,211 --> 01:36:01,839
No. Satnam was talking 
about another wave...

1158
01:36:02,006 --> 01:36:02,631
...coming from the east.

1159
01:36:07,094 --> 01:36:09,555
- Holy mother. 
- The flooding is gonna hit earlier?

1160
01:36:09,722 --> 01:36:12,433
is that what you're telling me? 
The second wave is closer?

1161
01:36:12,600 --> 01:36:14,560
- Plug in the new data. 
- Okay.

1162
01:36:16,479 --> 01:36:18,731
When's it gonna get here? Talk to me, 
Helmsley. When's it gonna hit?

1163
01:36:19,815 --> 01:36:21,484
Adjust the countdown.

1164
01:36:37,625 --> 01:36:40,503
Twenty-eight minutes, 
10 seconds to impact.

1165
01:36:40,669 --> 01:36:41,921
Oh, my God.

1166
01:36:42,087 --> 01:36:45,549
Captain, I need to speak to the other 
heads of state immediately.

1167
01:36:45,716 --> 01:36:48,511
- Right away. Taylor? 
- Aye, captain. Standing by.

1168
01:36:48,677 --> 01:36:51,263
Ark 6, stand by. Ark 7, stand by.

1169
01:36:51,430 --> 01:36:54,099
- Carl Anheuser, acting CIC, Ark 4. 
- Yes, sir.

1170
01:36:54,266 --> 01:36:56,560
Requesting emergency conference, 
T-99.

1171
01:37:32,888 --> 01:37:35,724
Attention: All construction workers, 
off deck.

1172
01:37:36,141 --> 01:37:39,019
All crew members, onboard now.

1173
01:37:39,186 --> 01:37:40,938
They're opening the mountain.

1174
01:37:41,397 --> 01:37:44,149
They are leaving without us.

1175
01:37:44,316 --> 01:37:47,611
Step back. Get back. 
What did I tell you?

1176
01:37:47,778 --> 01:37:50,698
They are leaving you behind too. 
Look, idiot.

1177
01:37:50,865 --> 01:37:52,950
Please be patient.

1178
01:37:55,578 --> 01:37:57,079
Let's go.

1179
01:38:00,124 --> 01:38:06,797
Follow me.

1180
01:38:19,059 --> 01:38:21,061
initiate security procedures.

1181
01:38:21,228 --> 01:38:25,858
Time to impact: 
17 minutes, 42 seconds.

1182
01:38:35,910 --> 01:38:37,828
Green lights on pressure, 
Mr. Anton?

1183
01:38:37,995 --> 01:38:40,039
Green lights across the board, 
captain.

1184
01:38:51,800 --> 01:38:53,177
Why do they have anchors?

1185
01:38:53,344 --> 01:38:56,639
Because they're not spaceships, 
buddy. They're arks.

1186
01:38:56,805 --> 01:38:58,390
Let's go.

1187
01:39:43,394 --> 01:39:44,436
Stop.

1188
01:39:44,603 --> 01:39:46,230
Stop! Stop!

1189
01:39:47,648 --> 01:39:48,691
Stop!

1190
01:39:55,280 --> 01:39:56,782
Engage the support mechanisms.

1191
01:39:56,949 --> 01:39:59,159
Aye, aye, captain. 
Engaging bow-anchor supports.

1192
01:39:59,326 --> 01:40:02,121
How long are these things expecting 
to hold us in place?

1193
01:40:02,287 --> 01:40:05,249
They're just meant to withstand 
the first impact of the waves.

1194
01:40:31,817 --> 01:40:51,044
Caesar.

1195
01:40:53,881 --> 01:40:55,340
Good. Good boy.

1196
01:40:55,799 --> 01:40:57,968
Come to Mommy. Caesar!

1197
01:40:59,261 --> 01:41:01,138
Mom, where's Tamara?

1198
01:41:03,432 --> 01:41:04,683
Daddy look!

1199
01:41:06,101 --> 01:41:08,187
Come on. Caesar, come on.

1200
01:41:08,353 --> 01:41:10,063
- Tamara! 
- I'm coming.

1201
01:41:18,030 --> 01:41:19,656
Take him.

1202
01:41:50,145 --> 01:41:51,522
The people of Russia...

1203
01:41:53,732 --> 01:41:54,900
...along with China...

1204
01:41:57,152 --> 01:42:00,155
...and Japan, agree.

1205
01:42:01,198 --> 01:42:03,116
Open the gates.

1206
01:42:05,160 --> 01:42:09,206
The United Kingdom, 
Spain, France, Canada, Germany...

1207
01:42:09,373 --> 01:42:13,836
...and I believe I may also speak 
for the Italian prime minister...

1208
01:42:14,002 --> 01:42:16,755
...we vote to let these people 
come in.

1209
01:42:22,845 --> 01:42:24,513
Captain Michaels.

1210
01:42:26,056 --> 01:42:27,224
Please.

1211
01:42:31,144 --> 01:42:32,688
This is the captain.

1212
01:42:32,855 --> 01:42:35,440
in a few moments, 
we will open the gates...

1213
01:42:35,607 --> 01:42:37,401
...and get you people in.

1214
01:42:37,568 --> 01:42:41,113
Please step back 
and clear the platform.

1215
01:42:43,574 --> 01:42:45,909
P- yew, it stinks.

1216
01:43:04,845 --> 01:43:07,222
- They are opening the gates. 
- Go. Go.

1217
01:43:07,389 --> 01:43:09,725
Climb! Don't look down! Climb! Go!

1218
01:43:15,564 --> 01:43:16,899
What's wrong with the gate?

1219
01:43:17,065 --> 01:43:20,068
Looks like it didn't run the full cycle. 
We're checking, captain.

1220
01:43:20,777 --> 01:43:21,862
Hold it.

1221
01:43:22,863 --> 01:43:23,906
Hold it, people.

1222
01:43:28,493 --> 01:43:31,038
Four minutes to impact.

1223
01:44:14,957 --> 01:44:16,500
Go to the lower deck. Let's go.

1224
01:44:16,667 --> 01:44:19,503
- We are loaded, captain. 
- Well, then let's lock it up. Now.

1225
01:44:35,644 --> 01:44:39,231
Captain, 
Cho Ming Airfield's been hit.

1226
01:44:39,398 --> 01:44:41,149
Put me on emergency com, 
Mr. Taylor.

1227
01:44:41,316 --> 01:44:43,652
Aye. You're on, captain.

1228
01:44:43,819 --> 01:44:45,237
This is the captain speaking.

1229
01:44:46,321 --> 01:44:49,074
We expect to be impacted 
by water shortly.

1230
01:45:02,462 --> 01:45:05,340
All stations, prepare for impact.

1231
01:45:44,921 --> 01:45:47,174
Collision pressure 
just below 80 pascal, captain.

1232
01:45:47,340 --> 01:45:49,885
0.2 mil surface compression 
on bow sensors, captain.

1233
01:45:50,010 --> 01:45:51,845
track Dr. Helmsley

1234
01:45:53,180 --> 01:45:54,222
Professor...

1235
01:45:55,057 --> 01:45:56,892
...it's Air Force One.

1236
01:46:14,493 --> 01:46:16,995
- The mid-ship anchor is hit. 
- We're destabilizing.

1237
01:46:17,162 --> 01:46:18,455
The bow anchor's giving in.

1238
01:46:53,657 --> 01:46:55,200
impact warning.

1239
01:46:55,367 --> 01:46:57,244
Thirty degrees west.

1240
01:46:57,410 --> 01:46:59,162
Forty-five degrees east.

1241
01:46:59,329 --> 01:47:02,207
Target elevation, 29,035 feet.

1242
01:47:02,290 --> 01:47:04,543
We're headed straight 
for the north face...

1243
01:47:04,709 --> 01:47:06,878
...of Mount Everest, Mr. Anheuser.

1244
01:47:07,045 --> 01:47:11,633
And if we can't start our engines, 
we will not survive the impact.

1245
01:47:20,809 --> 01:47:24,771
Distance to impact: 1850 meters.

1246
01:47:37,242 --> 01:47:40,120
Distance to impact: 400 meters.

1247
01:47:40,287 --> 01:47:43,123
Underwater ridge ahead. 
We're going to run aground, captain.

1248
01:47:46,751 --> 01:47:49,337
- Sir, the gate is sealed. 
- That's affirmative, captain.

1249
01:47:49,504 --> 01:47:51,381
Anton, start the engine.

1250
01:47:51,548 --> 01:47:53,300
Aye, aye, captain. Full reverse.

1251
01:48:02,225 --> 01:48:06,438
- Too fast! We're not gonna make it. 
- Distance to impact: 50 meters.

1252
01:48:07,105 --> 01:48:08,356
Forty meters.

1253
01:48:32,047 --> 01:48:34,174
Reverse motion activated.

1254
01:48:34,341 --> 01:48:37,802
Distance to impact: 10 meters.

1255
01:48:38,428 --> 01:48:39,596
Twenty meters.

1256
01:48:48,188 --> 01:48:49,522
Yes!

1257
01:48:54,402 --> 01:48:56,696
- Hard to port. 
- Aye, captain. Hard to port.

1258
01:49:25,642 --> 01:49:27,060
The end. "

1259
01:49:25,684 --> 01:49:27,811
Ladies and gentlemen, 
this is Captain Michaels speaking.

1260
01:49:28,895 --> 01:49:32,190
in a few minutes I will give orders 
to unseal the decks.

1261
01:49:32,190 --> 01:49:34,442
- Come on. 
- At 2345 last night...

1262
01:49:34,609 --> 01:49:38,780
...our sister arks, Numbers 6 and 7, 
have joined our course.

1263
01:49:40,323 --> 01:49:41,992
For the first time on ourjourney...

1264
01:49:42,158 --> 01:49:45,161
...we'll have clear skies 
and moderate-to-good air quality.

1265
01:49:45,328 --> 01:49:48,623
As you know, our passenger count 
is way over capacity.

1266
01:49:48,790 --> 01:49:51,251
So please be careful 
when you step out.

1267
01:49:51,418 --> 01:49:55,171
And of course, enjoy the fresh air.

1268
01:49:57,215 --> 01:49:58,341
Can I hold him?

1269
01:49:59,050 --> 01:50:01,678
Sure. He can be your dog too, 
if you like.

1270
01:50:01,845 --> 01:50:03,013
Thanks.

1271
01:50:07,100 --> 01:50:10,478
- Where have you been all my life? 
- Gift shop.

1272
01:51:07,327 --> 01:51:09,746
Oh, Adrian, excellent.

1273
01:51:10,163 --> 01:51:12,916
I called because we just got 
our first satellite feed.

1274
01:51:13,083 --> 01:51:15,585
The equalization 
of the oceanic seabeds...

1275
01:51:15,752 --> 01:51:18,254
...has not turned out 
to be as extreme as we expected.

1276
01:51:18,421 --> 01:51:22,092
The waters are receding much faster 
than we thought, thank God.

1277
01:51:22,258 --> 01:51:24,052
And this is hard to believe...

1278
01:51:24,219 --> 01:51:27,263
...but the Himalayas 
are no longer the roof of the world.

1279
01:51:27,430 --> 01:51:30,683
it's now the Drakensberg mountains 
of KwaZulu-Natal.

1280
01:51:30,850 --> 01:51:32,936
The entire African continent 
has risen.

1281
01:51:33,103 --> 01:51:36,064
Several thousand feet, 
and it likely never even flooded.

1282
01:51:36,231 --> 01:51:38,608
That's why they call it 
the Cape of Good Hope.

1283
01:51:38,775 --> 01:51:40,568
We've already set course for it.

1284
01:51:47,742 --> 01:51:49,661
Daddy, 
when will we go back home?

1285
01:51:50,495 --> 01:51:51,788
Well, we talked about that.

1286
01:51:51,955 --> 01:51:55,625
We're gonna find a new home 
out here somewhere, right?

1287
01:51:55,792 --> 01:51:58,545
I mean, wherever we're all together, 
that's home.

1288
01:51:58,712 --> 01:52:01,005
Right? Don't be scared.

1289
01:52:01,172 --> 01:52:02,799
I'm not.

1290
01:52:04,592 --> 01:52:06,136
No more Pull-Ups.

1291
01:52:09,472 --> 01:52:10,932
Nice.

